Centre National de la Recherche Scientifique, 38402 Saint-Martin-d'Hères, France; Koehl, M., Equipe Photogrammetrie et Geomatique, Modeles et Simulations pour l'Arch., l'Urban., et le Paysage-Photogrammetrie Architecturale et Geomatique UMR 694, Institut National des Sciences Appliquees de Strasbourg, 67084 Strasbourg, France","Monitoring temperate glacier activity has become more and more necessary for economical and security reasons and as an indicator of the local effects of global climate change. Remote sensing data provide useful information on such complex geophysical objects, but they require specific processing techniques to cope with the difficult context of moving and changing features in high-relief areas. This paper presents the first results of a project involving four laboratories developing and combining specific methods to extract information from optical and synthetic aperture radar (SAR) data. Two different information sources are processed, namely: 1) airborne photography and 2) spaceborne C-band SAR interferometry. The difficulties and limitations of their processing in the context of Alpine glaciers are discussed and illustrated on two glaciers located in the Mont-Blanc area. The results obtained by aerial triangulation techniques provide digital terrain models with an accuracy that is better than 30 cm, which is compatible with the computation of volume balance and useful for precise georeferencing and slope measurement updating. The results obtained by SAR differential interferometry using European Remote Sensing Satellite images show that it is possible to measure temperate glacier surface velocity fields from October to April in one-day interferograms with approximately 20-m ground sampling. This allows to derive ice surface strain rate fields required to model the glacier flow. These different measurements are complementary to results obtained during the summer from satellite optical data and ground measurements that are available only in few accessible points. © 2007 IEEE.","Airborne photogrammetry; Digital terrain model (DTM); Synthetic aperture radar (InSAR) interferometry; Temperate glacier; Velocity field","Airborne photogrammetry; Digital terrain model (DTM); Mont-Blanc area; Temperate glaciers; Velocity fields; Climate change; Ice; Photogrammetry; Remote sensing; Satellite imagery; Space applications; Synthetic aperture radar; Synthetic apertures; Glaciers",,,,,,"(2001) Climate change 2001: The scientific basis, , http://www.grida.no/climate/ipcc_tar/wg1, IPCC, Online, Available; Dyurgerov, M.B., Mountain and subpolar glaciers show an increase in sensitivity to climate warming and intensification of the water cycle (2003) J. Hydrol, 282 (1-4), pp. 164-176; Richardson, S., Reynolds, J., An overview of glacial hazards in the Hymalayas (2000) Quat. Int, 65-66, pp. 31-47. , Apr; Kääb, A., Huggel, C., Fischer, L., Guex, S., Paul, F., Roer, I., Salzmann, N., Weidmann, Y., Remote sensing of glacier- and permafrost-related hazards in high mountains: An overview (2005) Nat. Hazards Earth Syst. Sci, 5 (4), pp. 527-554. , Jul; Braithwaite, R.J., Glacier mass balance: The first 50 years of international monitoring (2002) Prog. Phys. Geogr, 26 (1), pp. 76-95. , Mar; Kääb, A., Combination of SRTM3 and repeat ASTER data for deriving alpine glacier flow velocities in the Bhutan Himalayas (2005) Remote Sens. Environ, 94 (4), pp. 463-474. , Feb; Kargel, J., Abrams, M., Bishop, M., Bush, A., Hamilton, G., Jiskoot, H., Kääb, A., Wessels, R., Multispectral imaging contributions to global land ice measurements from space (2005) Remote Sens. Environ, 99 (1-2), pp. 187-219. , Nov; Régie de gestion des données des pays de savoie, , http://www.rgd73-74.fr, Online, Available; Kääb, A., Monitoring high mountain terrain deformation from repeated air- and spaceborne optical data: Examples using digital aerial imagery and ASTER data (2002) ISPRS J. Photogramm. Remote Sens, 57 (1-2), pp. 39-52. , Nov; Fox, J., Nuttall, A.M., 